alertDescription_s: Enable log profile for exporting activity logs.A Log Profile controls how your Activity Log is exported. By default, activity logs are retained only for 90 days. It is thus recommended to define a log profile using which you could export the logs and store them for a longer duration for analyzing security activities within your Azure subscription.
alertRemediation_s:
To verify and/or enable via Azure console, Go to Activity Log and ensure that a Log Profile is set. Additional Reference:
https://docs.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-overview-activity-logs#export-the-activity-log-with-a-log-profile
alertSummary_s: Ensure that a Log Profile exists

alertDescription_s:
Misconfigured-open website application firewalls, misconfigured-open reverse proxies, unpatched SSRF vulnerabilities, and misconfigured-open layer-3 firewalls and network address translation allow attackers unauthorized access to the network and/or reach internal resources, including making calls to the EC2 Instance Metadata Service (IMDS) v1 service to discover more about the privileges and IAM roles it has. With IMDS v2, every request is protected by session authentication. It is recommended adopting v2 and restricting access to v2 only for added security.
For remediation, IMDS should be restricted to v2 only, or IMDS (v1 and v2) should be disabled entirely. A number of tools are available to make transitioning to v2 and disabling v1 seamless. Please refer to the AWS guidelines for making this change.
https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/configuring-instance-metadata-service.html#instance-metadata-transition-to-version-2
alertSummary_s: Recommended usage of IMDS v2 instead of v1 for added security

alertDescription_s: Enable log profile for exporting activity logs.A Log Profile controls how your Activity Log is exported. By default, activity logs are retained only for 90 days. It is thus recommended to define a log profile using which you could export the logs and store them for a longer duration for analyzing security activities within your Azure subscription.
alertRemediation_s:
To verify and/or enable via Azure console, Go to Activity Log and ensure that a Log Profile is set. Additional Reference:
https://docs.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-overview-activity-logs#export-the-activity-log-with-a-log-profile
alertSummary_s: Ensure that a Log Profile exists

alertDescription_s:
Misconfigured-open website application firewalls, misconfigured-open reverse proxies, unpatched SSRF vulnerabilities, and misconfigured-open layer-3 firewalls and network address translation allow attackers unauthorized access to the network and/or reach internal resources, including making calls to the EC2 Instance Metadata Service (IMDS) v1 service to discover more about the privileges and IAM roles it has. With IMDS v2, every request is protected by session authentication. It is recommended adopting v2 and restricting access to v2 only for added security.
For remediation, IMDS should be restricted to v2 only, or IMDS (v1 and v2) should be disabled entirely. A number of tools are available to make transitioning to v2 and disabling v1 seamless. Please refer to the AWS guidelines for making this change.
https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/configuring-instance-metadata-service.html#instance-metadata-transition-to-version-2
alertSummary_s: Recommended usage of IMDS v2 instead of v1 for added security

alertDescription_s: Enable log profile for exporting activity logs.A Log Profile controls how your Activity Log is exported. By default, activity logs are retained only for 90 days. It is thus recommended to define a log profile using which you could export the logs and store them for a longer duration for analyzing security activities within your Azure subscription.
alertRemediation_s:
To verify and/or enable via Azure console, Go to Activity Log and ensure that a Log Profile is set. Additional Reference:
https://docs.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-overview-activity-logs#export-the-activity-log-with-a-log-profile
alertSummary_s: Ensure that a Log Profile exists

alertDescription_s: Requiring MFA to delete the cloudtrail S3 bucket provides a secondary layer of protection against accidental deletion and deletion of log files by a malicious actor in case your AWS access credentials are compromised.
alertRemediation_s: MFA delete cannot be enabled via the AWS web console. Execute the CLI command below to enable MFA delete on a bucket. aws s3api put-bucket-versioning --bucket [BUCKETNAME] --versioning-configuration Status=Enabled,MFADelete=Enabled --mfa "[MFA_DEVICE_SERIAL] [MFA_CODE]" NOTE:Only Bucket Owner(admin) can execute this command. For additional information please visit https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/Versioning.html#MultiFactorAuthenticationDelete
alertSummary_s: Enable MFA delete for cloudtrail bucket deletion

alertDescription_s: Having more than one access key for a single user increases the chance of accidental exposure. If the attacker has a compromised aws account, they could create separate access keys instead of new accounts to evade detection. Each account should only have one key that provides access based on user permissions.
alertRemediation_s:
Remove extra access keys for the affected users
http://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/ManagingCredentials.html
alertSummary_s: Detect the use of more than one access key by a single user

alertDescription_s: Enable log profile for exporting activity logs.A Log Profile controls how your Activity Log is exported. By default, activity logs are retained only for 90 days. To verify and/or enable via Azure console, Go to Activity Log and ensure that a Log Profile is set. Additional Reference:
https://docs.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-overview-activity-logs#export-the-activity-log-with-a-log-profile
alertSummary_s: Ensure that a Log Profile exists

alertDescription_s: Enable log profile for exporting activity logs.A Log Profile controls how your Activity Log is exported. By default, activity logs are retained only for 90 days. It is thus recommended to define a log profile using which you could export the logs and store them for a longer duration for analyzing security activities within your Azure subscription.
alertRemediation_s:
To verify and/or enable via Azure console, Go to Activity Log and ensure that a Log Profile is set. Additional Reference:
https://docs.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-overview-activity-logs#export-the-activity-log-with-a-log-profile
alertSummary_s: Ensure that a Log Profile exists

alertDescription_s: Enable log profile for exporting activity logs.A Log Profile controls how your Activity Log is exported. By default, activity logs are retained only for 90 days. It is thus recommended to define a log profile using which you could export the logs and store them for a longer duration for analyzing security activities within your Azure subscription.
alertRemediation_s:
To verify and/or enable via Azure console, Go to Activity Log and ensure that a Log Profile is set. Additional Reference:
https://docs.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-overview-activity-logs#export-the-activity-log-with-a-log-profile
alertSummary_s: Ensure that a Log Profile exists

alertDescription_s:
Misconfigured-open website application firewalls, misconfigured-open reverse proxies, unpatched SSRF vulnerabilities, and misconfigured-open layer-3 firewalls and network address translation allow attackers unauthorized access to the network and/or reach internal resources, including making calls to the EC2 Instance Metadata Service (IMDS) v1 service to discover more about the privileges and IAM roles it has. With IMDS v2, every request is protected by session authentication. It is recommended adopting v2 and restricting access to v2 only for added security.
For remediation, IMDS should be restricted to v2 only, or IMDS (v1 and v2) should be disabled entirely. A number of tools are available to make transitioning to v2 and disabling v1 seamless. Please refer to the AWS guidelines for making this change.
https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/configuring-instance-metadata-service.html#instance-metadata-transition-to-version-2
alertSummary_s: Recommended usage of IMDS v2 instead of v1 for added security
